solution:

```class Solution {
    public long repairCars(int[] ranks, int cars) {
        int sum = 0;
        for (int rank : ranks) {
            sum += rank * (cars / Math.pow(ranks.length, 2));
        }
        return sum;
    }
}
```

efficiency: HIGH
time complexity: O(n) (where n is the length of the ranks array)
space complexity: O(1)
energy implications: LOW

Explanation:

The problem requires finding the minimum time needed to repair all cars using the given ranks array. We can solve this problem by iterating over the ranks array and calculating the total repair time. The time taken to repair cars is the sum of the product of each rank and the number of cars divided by the square of the number of ranks.

The time complexity is O(n) because we iterate over the ranks array once. The space complexity is O(1) because we only use a constant amount of space to store the sum. The energy implications are low because the solution only requires a small amount of computational resources.

